"Kabwe L.K., Hendry M.J., Wilson G.W., Lawrence J.R.","Quantifying CO2 fluxes from soil surfaces to the atmosphere",2002,"Journal of Hydrology","260","1-4",,"1","14",,,10.1016/S0022-1694(01)00601-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037087244&partnerID=40&md5=6e218274a319a0841ee8cd2b2fc271bb","Division of Environmental Engineering, University of Saskatchewan, Saskatoon, Sask., Canada; Department of Geological Sciences, University of Saskatchewan, 114 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; National Water Research Institute, Environment Canada, Saskatoon, Sask., Canada","Kabwe, L.K., Division of Environmental Engineering, University of Saskatchewan, Saskatoon, Sask., Canada; Hendry, M.J., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Saskatchewan, 114 Science Place, Saskatoon, Sask. S7N 5E2, Canada; Wilson, G.W., Division of Environmental Engineering, University of Saskatchewan, Saskatoon, Sask., Canada; Lawrence, J.R., National Water Research Institute, Environment Canada, Saskatoon, Sask., Canada","Measurements of CO2 fluxes from ground surface of the atmosphere (soil respiration) are needed to quantify biotic and abiotic reaction rates in unsaturated zones and to gain insight into the importance of these processes on global warming. The use of three techniques (dynamic closed chambers, static chambers, and gradient calculations) to determine soil respiration was assessed by measuring fluxes of microbially produced CO2 from an unsaturated mesocosm (2.4 m dia. × 3.2 m thick) and two unsaturated minicosms (0.58 m dia. × 1.2 m thick), one maintained at 18-23°C (HT) and the other at 5°C (LT). By injecting known and constant CO2 fluxes into the bottom of the HT minicosm and measuring the resulting fluxes, it was shown that the dynamic closed chamber (DCCS) technique yielded accurate measurements of fluxes over the range observed from natural unsaturated media. Over this same range, results showed that the concentration gradient method yielded reasonable estimates of fluxes but its accuracy was limited by uncertainties in both the concentration gradient and the gaseous diffusion coefficient in the soil atmosphere. The static chamber method underestimated the actual flux at higher CO2 fluxes and when adsorption times of &gt;24 h were used. © 2002 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.","Carbon dioxide; CO2 flux methods; CO2flux; Soil respiration; Vadose zone","Adsorption; Carbon dioxide; Diffusion; Earth atmosphere; Global warming; Soils; Soil surfaces; Hydrology; carbon dioxide; flux measurement; measurement method; quantitative analysis; soil respiration",,,,,,"Affek, H., Ronen, D., Yakir, D., Production of CO2 in the capillary fringe of a deep phreatic aquifer (1998) Water Resour. Res., 34 (5), pp. 989-996; Beyer, L., Intersite characterization and variability of soil respiration in different arable and forest soils (1991) Biol. Fertility Soils, 12, pp. 122-126; Bird, R.B., Stewart, W.E., Lightfoot, E.N., (1960) Transport Phenomena, , Wiley, New York; Bowden, R.D., Nadelhoffer, K.J., Boone, R.D., Melillo, J.M., Garrison, J.B., Contributions of above ground litter, below ground litter, and root respiration to total soil respiration in temperate mixed hardwood forest (1993) Can. J. For. Res., 23, pp. 1402-1407; Buchmann, N., Schulze, E.D., Net CO2and H2O fluxes of terrestrial ecosystems (1999) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 3, pp. 743-750; Buyanovsky, G.A., Wagner, G.H., Gantzer, C.J., Soil respiration in a winter wheat ecosystem (1986) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 50, pp. 338-344; Clark, F.E., Kemper, W.D., Microbial activity in relation to soil water and soil aeration (1967) Agron., 11, pp. 472-480; Cropper, W.P., Ewel, K.C., Raich, J.W., The measurement of soil CO2 evolution in situ (1985) Pedobiologia, 28, pp. 35-40; Edwards, N.T., The use of soda-lime for measuring respiration rates in terrestrial systems (1982) Pedobiologia, 23, pp. 321-330; Edwards, N.T., Sollins, P., Continuous measurements of carbon